If we talk about methods of empirical observation,

04:05.000 --> 04:10.000
then we need to focus on three of them.

04:10.000 --> 04:16.000
These are observation, comparison, and measurement, including experiments.

04:16.000 --> 04:18.000
Let's start with observation.

04:18.000 --> 04:24.000
I will not dwell on these methods in great detail,

04:24.000 --> 04:26.000
let's say, on observation,

04:26.000 --> 04:34.000
because you will hear about observation in addition to other courses,

04:34.000 --> 04:37.000
for example, organizational behavior.

04:37.000 --> 04:46.000
Nevertheless, the main principles that are characteristic not only for conducting research in the field of organizational behavior,

04:46.000 --> 04:50.000
but also general principles, we must consider.

04:50.000 --> 04:52.000
So, what is observation?

04:52.000 --> 04:54.000
The definition is written on the slide.

04:54.000 --> 05:00.000
It is a system of fixing and registering the properties of the connection of the studied object

05:00.000 --> 05:09.000
in natural conditions or in artificial circumstances, that is, within the framework of the experiment.

05:09.000 --> 05:15.000
In fact, we are all observers in one way or another,

05:15.000 --> 05:23.000
and observing the processes, phenomena, we make certain conclusions and make decisions.

05:23.000 --> 05:32.000
Therefore, observation is one of the most common methods of research in business.

05:32.000 --> 05:37.000
There are two types of observation.

05:37.000 --> 05:44.000
These are unstructured observations, which are also called included observations,

05:44.000 --> 05:47.000
and structured observations.

05:47.000 --> 05:56.000
In the first case, the researcher is inside the situation,

05:57.000 --> 06:10.000
he is studying this situation, and his task may be to clarify the problem that was originally formulated

06:10.000 --> 06:15.000
or to form a working hypothesis.

06:15.000 --> 06:22.000
Structured observation is usually carried out to describe the repeatability,

06:22.000 --> 06:30.000
the typicalness of the occurrence of one or another phenomenon, behavior, and so on.

06:30.000 --> 06:33.000
What is included observation?

06:33.000 --> 06:37.000
Quoting from the textbook, we read,

06:37.000 --> 06:45.000
The researcher strives to take part in the life of the participants in the study and their activities,

06:45.000 --> 06:51.000
that is, he is inside the team, inside the situation.

06:51.000 --> 06:59.000
He strives to become a member of this group, this organization or this community.

06:59.000 --> 07:01.000
What is it for?

07:01.000 --> 07:12.000
In order to understand their thoughts, feelings, reactions to certain events,

07:12.000 --> 07:18.000
their inner motives, which they may not tell, for example, during an interview.

07:18.000 --> 07:26.000
And all this is passed through the observer through himself,

07:26.000 --> 07:32.000
through the prism of his own experiences, perceptions, emotions, and so on.

07:32.000 --> 07:40.000
Of course, the question arises, how unpredictable is such a method of study?

07:40.000 --> 07:46.000
But this is a separate question, and we will definitely talk about it.

07:47.000 --> 07:56.000
Being an observer, an included observer, the researcher can perform different roles.

07:56.000 --> 07:58.000
As shown on the slide.

07:58.000 --> 08:04.000
He can be a pure participant, a pure observer,

08:04.000 --> 08:10.000
he can be a participating observer, that is, he is a participant, but also an observer,

08:10.000 --> 08:14.000
and can play the role of an observing participant.

08:15.000 --> 08:23.000
This method assumes, as a rule, the obtaining of high-quality data.

08:23.000 --> 08:28.000
That is, what will the observer describe, record?

08:28.000 --> 08:30.000
What he sees.

08:30.000 --> 08:39.000
And make notes, how people react to some change in the organization,

08:39.000 --> 08:49.000
to the comments of, say, the leader, how the relations between them are formed, and so on.

08:49.000 --> 08:54.000
What is the difference between these four roles?

08:54.000 --> 09:04.000
In the first two cases, we say that people do not know that they are being observed.

09:04.000 --> 09:09.000
That is, there is a so-called hidden observation.

09:09.000 --> 09:12.000
Is it good or bad?

09:12.000 --> 09:15.000
Which side to look at?

09:15.000 --> 09:23.000
If we talk about the unpredictability, the unbiasedness of the data,

09:24.000 --> 09:32.000
then for the purpose of the experiment, for the purpose of observation, for the purpose of the result,

09:32.000 --> 09:38.000
it is better if people do not know that they are being observed.

09:38.000 --> 09:47.000
Because nature is such that if we are being observed, we behave differently.

09:47.000 --> 09:55.000
In this case, the researcher can get distorted data and come to an incorrect result.

09:55.000 --> 09:59.000
But, there is a big but.

09:59.000 --> 10:04.000
And this but is on the ethical side of the matter.

10:04.000 --> 10:10.000
We will talk about ethics today, but nevertheless it is important to say now

10:10.000 --> 10:16.000
that we are violating some human rights.

10:16.000 --> 10:22.000
And later on, it can make us feel some kind of complaint.

10:22.000 --> 10:25.000
But for the researcher, this is very important.

10:25.000 --> 10:33.000
In fact, he gets some kind of intelligence data, not just priceless for subsequent analysis.

10:33.000 --> 10:38.000
How can a hidden observation be carried out?

10:38.000 --> 10:45.000
In the first case, a person simply introduces what we call a hidden Cossack.

10:45.000 --> 10:48.000
No one can guess that he is not one of us.

10:48.000 --> 10:55.000
He lives the same life, performs the same tasks as his colleagues, and so on.

10:55.000 --> 10:57.000
There is a danger here.

10:57.000 --> 11:09.000
In that the observer can start to prejudge certain phenomena.

11:09.000 --> 11:16.000
That is, he penetrates this atmosphere, he enters the position of his people around him.

11:16.000 --> 11:26.000
And there is a great danger that he will prejudge something that is happening.

11:26.000 --> 11:31.000
Avoiding this allows for the so-called hidden observation

11:31.000 --> 11:35.000
using the technical means of hidden observation.

11:35.000 --> 11:38.000
When a camera is watching people.

11:38.000 --> 11:43.000
Or you probably saw it in the movies, when an experiment is being carried out.

11:43.000 --> 11:49.000
Behind a transparent glass, only on one side, there are investigators,

11:49.000 --> 11:55.000
and, let's say, a powerful stake of suspects is being played.

11:55.000 --> 11:58.000
There are, of course, some nuances here.

11:58.000 --> 12:02.000
In this case, such an observation is generally cleared.

12:02.000 --> 12:07.000
At least, the observer becomes completely independent.

12:07.000 --> 12:13.000
The ethical side remains the same, people are being watched.

12:13.000 --> 12:18.000
But this situation can be managed in modern conditions.

12:18.000 --> 12:27.000
And most often in modern organizations, when a contract is signed for work,

12:27.000 --> 12:34.000
one of the points is that a person is made aware in advance

12:34.000 --> 12:39.000
that a hidden observation can be carried out behind him.

12:39.000 --> 12:43.000
For an investigator, such a contract is just a gift.

12:43.000 --> 12:49.000
The next two situations suggest that people know

12:49.000 --> 12:56.000
that there is a person in their team who is watching them.

12:56.000 --> 12:59.000
Thus, we solve the ethical side of the issue.

12:59.000 --> 13:08.000
But there is still such a drawback as the influence of the investigator on the participants of this study

13:08.000 --> 13:13.000
and the opposite, the influence of the participants on the investigator.

13:13.000 --> 13:18.000
These problems can be avoided or reduced to a minimum

13:18.000 --> 13:23.000
if a person has been watching people for a long enough time.

13:23.000 --> 13:27.000
A person gets tired of thinking about what is being watched.

13:27.000 --> 13:32.000
And he begins to perceive the investigator as his own.

13:32.000 --> 13:39.000
And then, in general, it is possible to minimize the negative consequences.

13:39.000 --> 13:44.000
The methods of included observation have their advantages and disadvantages.

13:44.000 --> 13:47.000
As, however, any method has.

13:47.000 --> 13:51.000
There is not a single method that we could call ideal.

13:51.000 --> 13:54.000
There is no ideal methodology.

13:54.000 --> 14:00.000
That is why we are studying a number of methods so that you can choose the best one

14:00.000 --> 14:06.000
