Structured observation differs from the included one in that its main goal is to obtain quantitative data.

21:16.000 --> 21:28.000
Researchers are interested in how often a particular phenomenon, event, or human action is repeated.

21:28.000 --> 21:43.000
Structured observation is not aimed at investigating the causes of this phenomenon, but at determining the periodicity of its occurrence.

21:43.000 --> 21:54.000
Since we are focusing on qualitative data, we will not go into details of structured observation.

21:54.000 --> 22:02.000
I will just say that structured observation is usually done using special techniques for recording.

22:02.000 --> 22:07.000
Either control sheets, or diaries, and so on.

22:07.000 --> 22:12.000
The next method is an empirical method.

22:12.000 --> 22:17.000
Let me remind you that we are still looking at methods of empirical research.

22:17.000 --> 22:30.000
An experiment is an experimental study of the impact of a particular factor or group of factors on a variable researcher.

22:30.000 --> 22:43.000
That is, a certain distinguishing feature, characteristic of an object that can be changed, tracked, and measured.

22:43.000 --> 22:46.000
Not always measured, but still.

22:46.000 --> 22:48.000
The types of experiments.

22:48.000 --> 22:55.000
To make it short, let me emphasize that there are two types of experiments.

22:55.000 --> 23:04.000
A laboratory experiment, or so-called true experiment, and a field experiment that is conducted in natural conditions.

23:04.000 --> 23:10.000
What is a good laboratory experiment?

23:10.000 --> 23:19.000
In essence, an artificial environment is created, a so-called model experiment is conducted,

23:19.000 --> 23:30.000
when the impact of external or some other factors on the variable researcher is reduced to a minimum.

23:30.000 --> 23:37.000
To give you an example of a true experiment, it is most often used in technical sciences.

23:37.000 --> 23:40.000
The crash test is probably well known to everyone.

23:40.000 --> 23:43.000
In essence, it is an experiment.

23:43.000 --> 23:50.000
The designers have created a car, and it is necessary to assess the degree of its safety.

23:50.000 --> 23:53.000
It is accelerated and hit against the wall.

23:53.000 --> 23:59.000
And they look at the dynamics of the car's destruction, how badly these people will suffer.

23:59.000 --> 24:03.000
But destroying a whole car is quite an expensive pleasure.

24:03.000 --> 24:09.000
Therefore, in laboratory conditions, a model can be made.

24:09.000 --> 24:15.000
In fact, there is only one chair, the structures that surround the person,

24:15.000 --> 24:24.000
and a doll with sensors and its cover is placed in it.

24:24.000 --> 24:27.000
And to see what breaks at the doll's neck or leg.

24:28.000 --> 24:39.000
A field experiment is conducted in natural conditions, when the researcher does not change anything in the surrounding environment.

24:39.000 --> 24:50.000
This experiment is quite complex, because the system is very multifaceted, but also very informative and effective.

24:51.000 --> 24:52.000
What should be noted?

24:52.000 --> 25:01.000
An experiment can be carried out, as it is good for obtaining quantitative data, for example,

25:01.000 --> 25:04.000
the time to develop equipment for failure.

25:04.000 --> 25:05.000
What is it?

25:05.000 --> 25:12.000
They have developed a new telephone device, they have given it to a person to use,

25:12.000 --> 25:16.000
and he must hand it over when it breaks.

25:16.000 --> 25:23.000
If they gave it to 100 people, then you can already draw some statistical conclusions,

25:23.000 --> 25:28.000
that on average it will serve 2 years, and then it is not needed.

25:30.000 --> 25:36.000
But the experiment is also good because it allows you to obtain qualitative characteristics.

25:36.000 --> 25:44.000
For example, if you study people's reaction to changes.

25:44.000 --> 25:49.000
It is difficult to record, but the experiment is very useful.

25:49.000 --> 25:53.000
There are several schemes for conducting experiments.

