because it is the main prerogative of quantitative methods of determination.

30:58.000 --> 31:07.000
That is, there is a procedure for determining the numerical value of a certain value.

31:07.000 --> 31:19.000
And this numerical value is determined by comparing the units of measurement and the object of study.

31:19.000 --> 31:32.000
This procedure is very important because it allows you to get very accurate quantitative data about the surrounding reality.

31:32.000 --> 31:37.000
The data obtained can be statistically processed,

31:37.000 --> 31:41.000
and the dependence can be identified, and so on.

31:41.000 --> 31:48.000
But this will be told in detail in the lecture on quantitative methods of study.

31:48.000 --> 31:54.000
And here we move on to the next group of general methods of study.

31:54.000 --> 32:03.000
We will list the methods that can be used both empirically and theoretically.

32:03.000 --> 32:05.000
There are quite a few of them.

32:05.000 --> 32:10.000
Abstraction, analysis-synthesis, induction-deduction, and so on.

32:10.000 --> 32:13.000
The first of the listed is abstraction.

32:13.000 --> 32:15.000
What is abstraction?

32:15.000 --> 32:18.000
I think that all of you have heard this term.

32:18.000 --> 32:23.000
But for our purposes, we must consider two aspects.

32:23.000 --> 32:30.000
There is the concept of the process of abstraction and the result of abstraction.

32:30.000 --> 32:34.000
What is abstraction?

32:34.000 --> 32:36.000
What does it mean to abstract?

32:36.000 --> 32:38.000
You have probably heard this term.

32:38.000 --> 32:41.000
To abstract from circumstances.

32:41.000 --> 32:52.000
That is, to highlight the essential, important, central thing that should be assessed.

32:52.000 --> 32:56.000
That is, to simplify the complex.

32:56.000 --> 33:12.000
But what you leave in your abstraction should be absolutely unharmful to the object you tried to abstract.

33:12.000 --> 33:14.000
What is it for?

33:14.000 --> 33:23.000
To simplify the process of assessment and study of the object itself.

33:23.000 --> 33:28.000
What can you abstract from in the business environment?

33:28.000 --> 33:35.000
If you study, let's say, the motivation of employees,

33:35.000 --> 33:39.000
you are not interested in motivation at all,

33:39.000 --> 33:44.000
and the motivation is only material,

33:44.000 --> 33:50.000
then you can abstract from the non-material.

33:50.000 --> 34:04.000
If you continue, you can move away the non-essential, which is not important for your analysis,

34:04.000 --> 34:09.000
and focus only on the key points.

34:09.000 --> 34:16.000
Unfortunately, this is not a method used so often.

34:16.000 --> 34:20.000
It is complex and sometimes very subjective.

34:20.000 --> 34:23.000
The next method is analysis and synthesis.

34:23.000 --> 34:33.000
This method is practically the main, triangular one in any study.

34:33.000 --> 34:36.000
What is analysis?

34:36.000 --> 34:48.000
Analysis is the decomposition of the object into components, as shown in the following slide.

34:48.000 --> 34:52.000
But to decompose a whole into components,

34:52.000 --> 34:59.000
you need to highlight certain features of individual elements of a whole.

34:59.000 --> 35:08.000
By decomposing into components, each of them must be analyzed separately,

35:08.000 --> 35:12.000
significant interconnections must be highlighted,

35:12.000 --> 35:17.000
and then synthesis must be carried out.

35:17.000 --> 35:21.000
It turns out that synthesis is a process of reverse analysis.

35:21.000 --> 35:24.000
But pay attention to the diagram.

35:24.000 --> 35:32.000
In a synthesized object, we already have fewer elements,

35:32.000 --> 35:42.000
and we have otherwise organized their structure, their interconnections.

35:42.000 --> 35:51.000
This allows us to build our conclusions more correctly, to come to certain conclusions.

35:51.000 --> 35:53.000
Induction and deduction.

35:53.000 --> 35:56.000
We have talked about this a lot.

35:56.000 --> 35:59.000
What should be noted here?

35:59.000 --> 36:09.000
It is very important that the induction and deduction lead to the same results.

36:09.000 --> 36:17.000
If the inductively conducted study contradicts the theory,

36:17.000 --> 36:24.000
or if the data you have collected does not confirm the theory,

36:24.000 --> 36:28.000
then there are two possible outcomes of the situation.

36:28.000 --> 36:34.000
Either you conducted the study incorrectly, or you made a discovery.

36:34.000 --> 36:37.000
Historical and logical methods.

36:37.000 --> 36:41.000
Historically, they are also called the archival method.

36:41.000 --> 36:48.000
That is, it is the study of the history of events in all their complexity,

36:48.000 --> 36:55.000
of course, with the exception of those elements that interest the researcher.

36:55.000 --> 37:03.000
The logical method differs from the historical one in that it also studies history,

37:04.000 --> 37:12.000
but it studies the logic of the occurrence of certain events, the course of certain events.

37:12.000 --> 37:21.000
This is also a kind of abstraction, that is, the logic of the history of events

37:21.000 --> 37:33.000
is cleared of randomness, turns, zigzags that may coincide with the study of the event.

37:33.000 --> 37:40.000
Modeling is a very important method of study.

37:40.000 --> 37:43.000
What is a model?

37:43.000 --> 37:51.000
You can say that it is an analogue of a real object, or a phenomenon, or a process.

37:51.000 --> 37:55.000
But you need to be very careful.

37:55.000 --> 38:00.000
A model and an analogue are completely different concepts.

38:00.000 --> 38:05.000
There can be a lot of analogues,

38:05.000 --> 38:14.000
but this does not mean that analogues repeat the main significant aspects of the object being studied.

38:14.000 --> 38:24.000
But a model repeats the main significant aspects of the object being studied.

38:24.000 --> 38:30.000
In principle, there are physical models, which we most often call models,

38:30.000 --> 38:34.000
and there are abstract models.

38:34.000 --> 38:47.000
These can be sign systems, language models, virtual models, or mathematical models.

38:47.000 --> 38:51.000
Modeling is very widespread in research.

38:51.000 --> 38:59.000
Your workbook gives an example of how website creators work.

38:59.000 --> 39:06.000
When creating a website, a model is first of all created.

39:06.000 --> 39:13.000
It is not filled with all kinds of pictograms, links, and so on.

39:13.000 --> 39:19.000
The model has only the basic working tools.

39:19.000 --> 39:25.000
This allows website developers to check, for example, how interfaces work,

39:25.000 --> 39:30.000
how convenient it is for users to work with this website, and so on.

39:30.000 --> 39:39.000
When this model website is finished, it can be filled with other elements,

39:39.000 --> 39:44.000
which may be less meaningful.

39:44.000 --> 39:51.000
In principle, a model can be called what I told you about crash tests.

39:51.000 --> 39:59.000
But in business, a certain scheme is often understood as a model.

39:59.000 --> 40:05.000
The next slide shows a model of strategic management.

40:05.000 --> 40:09.000
One of the possible ones, there are quite a few of them.

40:09.000 --> 40:18.000
Please note that the model shows the key aspects of strategic management.

40:18.000 --> 40:22.000
The basis of the basis is a business idea,

40:22.000 --> 40:29.000
around which target installations are formed,

40:29.000 --> 40:36.000
and then the development of all aspects of strategic management.

40:36.000 --> 40:41.000
The model of synthesis analysis was previously presented on the previous slide.

40:42.000 --> 40:50.000
There are so-called portfolio models in strategic management.

40:50.000 --> 40:53.000
What are the advantages of models?

40:53.000 --> 41:01.000
They are good because they allow you to study elements very well.

41:01.000 --> 41:14.000
They structure the course of thought and clearly and visually show you the structure of the object or subject of research.

41:14.000 --> 41:21.000
In principle, the creation of a model can be the goal of research.

41:21.000 --> 41:33.000
You can create a model of relationships with the management of your organization by conducting research.

41:33.000 --> 41:43.000
For example, I think that you will read about idealization, formalization and axiomatic method in your workbook.

41:43.000 --> 41:48.000
These methods are not used so often in the business environment.

41:48.000 --> 41:52.000
And we are moving on.

41:52.000 --> 42:00.000
Finally, we will discuss the topic of qualitative methods of research in business.

42:00.000 --> 42:09.000
We have already considered some of these methods, but we need to deepen and expand this information.

42:09.000 --> 42:16.000
First of all, it should be noted that qualitative and quantitative methods are by no means competitors.

42:16.000 --> 42:19.000
The difference between them is significant.

42:19.000 --> 42:24.000
Quantitative methods allow us to give a numerical assessment of events,

42:24.000 --> 42:30.000
and qualitative methods allow us to give an assessment of events,

42:30.000 --> 42:35.000
give a characteristic of what is happening, and so on.

42:35.000 --> 42:41.000
In one research, both qualitative and quantitative methods of analysis can be used.

42:41.000 --> 42:44.000
What precedes what?

42:44.000 --> 42:50.000
In fact, it depends on how you have built your research.

42:50.000 --> 42:54.000
Quantitative data can be collected,

42:54.000 --> 43:07.000
and in order to fully analyze and understand them, additional qualitative studies can be conducted for explanation.

43:07.000 --> 43:15.000
But it is quite possible that when qualitative studies are collected,

43:15.000 --> 43:20.000
a characteristic of the situation, object, phenomenon, and so on is given,

43:20.000 --> 43:26.000
which requires additional quantitative information.

43:26.000 --> 43:36.000
As we have already said, maybe we need to look at how often this phenomenon appears in a particular group, and so on.

43:36.000 --> 43:42.000
Quantitative and qualitative methods are complementary.

43:42.000 --> 43:53.000
Nevertheless, qualitative methods are very common in business and differ in some characteristics.

43:53.000 --> 44:03.000
First of all, qualitative methods of research imply the collection of information in a free form,

44:03.000 --> 44:07.000
that is, there is no specific structure.

44:07.000 --> 44:18.000
It is important that they rely on understanding and explanation of empirical data collected by a researcher.

44:18.000 --> 44:25.000
They serve as a source for forming hypotheses and some productive ideas.

44:25.000 --> 44:35.000
At the same time, qualitative studies can be used to collect information about bias, motivations, values, and so on.

44:35.000 --> 44:39.000
For example, when conducting marketing research,

44:39.000 --> 44:52.000
motives that incline people to buy this, not another product, to approach this brand, not another one, can be studied.

44:52.000 --> 45:01.000
Because they prefer one type of service, let's say, in a restaurant, and not another.

45:02.000 --> 45:03.000
What else is very important?

45:03.000 --> 45:07.000
Qualitative data allows us to understand the essence of the problem.

45:07.000 --> 45:13.000
Since we have talked about the study, explanatory type of research,

45:13.000 --> 45:19.000
then by studying the variety of elements and situations,

45:19.000 --> 45:29.000
we can thus create a base for subsequent quantitative research and quantitative assessment.

45:30.000 --> 45:38.000
As I have already said, qualitative research can be studied in quantitative ways,

45:38.000 --> 45:47.000
in this case, by performing the function of explaining the obtained quantitative data.

45:47.000 --> 45:55.000
The methods of qualitative research include interviews, focus groups, observations, and experiments.

45:55.000 --> 46:04.000
We have already talked about observations and experiments when we talked about general methods of research.

46:04.000 --> 46:15.000
Therefore, now we will focus on the interview and the variety of interviews, which is called focus groups.

46:15.000 --> 46:17.000
What is an interview?

46:17.000 --> 46:27.000
In fact, it is a purposeful discussion or conversation between two or more people,

46:27.000 --> 46:35.000
which is aimed at obtaining certain types of information from these people.

46:35.000 --> 46:38.000
There are three types of interviews.

46:38.000 --> 46:45.000
These are structured interviews, partially structured, and unstructured interviews,

46:45.000 --> 46:49.000
which are also called deep interviews.

46:49.000 --> 46:56.000
Let's look at each of these types of interviews separately.

46:56.000 --> 47:01.000
A structured interview is a standardized procedure,

47:01.000 --> 47:06.000
which is most often carried out by using surveys.

47:06.000 --> 47:08.000
What is a survey?

47:08.000 --> 47:18.000
It is a form with a certain number of questions.

47:18.000 --> 47:29.000
These questions are asked to all participants who are subject to this method of analysis.

47:29.000 --> 47:37.000
The example of a structured interview is shown in the application for the workbook.

47:37.000 --> 47:41.000
It is a fairly long document to talk about it here,

47:41.000 --> 47:48.000
but pay attention to how people who have passed a structured interview respond.

47:48.000 --> 47:53.000
One opinion was expressed that a structured interview is similar to a survey.

47:53.000 --> 48:00.000
You are asked a question, you are listened to, and you are asked the next question,

48:00.000 --> 48:05.000
which is not related to the previous one and your answer to the previous question.

48:05.000 --> 48:07.000
Why is this done?

48:07.000 --> 48:19.000
The thing is that the quality methods of research are mostly developed by psychologists.

48:19.000 --> 48:26.000
And the way a person responds to a question, for example, can be asked,

48:26.000 --> 48:32.000
tell me, please, a funny story from your life.

48:32.000 --> 48:42.000
A person tells a story, and the listener pays attention to his emotionality,

48:42.000 --> 48:50.000
to his ability to creatively process some information, to non-verbal signs,

48:50.000 --> 48:56.000
if we are talking about a personal structured interview, not a survey.

48:56.000 --> 49:03.000
A structured interview is most often used to collect quantitative data.

49:03.000 --> 49:05.000
Why?

49:05.000 --> 49:19.000
Because in addition to this questionnaire, there are developed methods of pain evaluation of the respondent's answer.

49:19.000 --> 49:23.000
The interviewer asks a question, and the questioner says,

49:23.000 --> 49:26.000
the questioner does not understand the meaning of the question,

49:26.000 --> 49:35.000
but the researcher has a methodology of evaluation of the respondent's emotionality,

49:35.000 --> 49:44.000
the person's stress resistance, the level of truthfulness or not.

49:44.000 --> 49:55.000
And so you can sum up the number of points, like in a psychological test.

49:55.000 --> 50:04.000
This method works very well, it allows to make a very large coverage of the interview,

50:04.000 --> 50:12.000
especially if it is not a personal survey, but is used mainly to get quantitative information.

50:12.000 --> 50:22.000
Unlike structured interviews, a partially structured interview should have a list of topics,

50:22.000 --> 50:29.000
not questions, like in a structured interview, but topics for discussion.

50:29.000 --> 50:32.000
Topics and questions.

50:32.000 --> 50:40.000
The main difference from a structured interview is that in the process of an interview,

50:40.000 --> 50:45.000
topics and questions can change.

50:45.000 --> 50:50.000
That is, the interviewer can, by the course of the interview,

50:50.000 --> 50:57.000
based on the respondent's answer, change the course of the interview.

50:57.000 --> 51:10.000
Let's say the respondent shows some impatience or irritation from the questions.

51:10.000 --> 51:19.000
The researcher can change the tone, the order of the questions,

51:19.000 --> 51:29.000
or exclude some topics of a personal nature that the respondent is affected by from this interview.

51:29.000 --> 51:33.000
And, accordingly, change the direction of the conversation.

51:33.000 --> 51:43.000
Partially structured and unstructured interviews are intended for quality research.

51:43.000 --> 51:53.000
That is, the researcher needs to understand the feeling, the experience, the motivation, and so on.

51:53.000 --> 52:04.000
The reaction to certain events, in order to answer the research question later.

52:05.000 --> 52:13.000
An unstructured interview or a deep interview is always informal.

52:13.000 --> 52:20.000
The researcher usually does not have a list of questions prepared in advance,

52:20.000 --> 52:29.000
but he must clearly imagine what problems he wants to study.

52:30.000 --> 52:38.000
And he already formulates the questions as the respondent answers them.

52:38.000 --> 52:46.000
It is quite possible that in the course of an unstructured interview, new problems will be revealed,

52:46.000 --> 52:51.000
which will be subject to further study or research.

52:52.000 --> 53:05.000
An unstructured interview is very often conducted with people who are in a high position in society or in business,

53:05.000 --> 53:12.000
and do not want everyone to know what they are talking about in this interview.

53:12.000 --> 53:19.000
That is, it is a personal conversation between the researcher and the respondent.

53:19.000 --> 53:25.000
But a deep interview is a very powerful research tool,

53:25.000 --> 53:32.000
which allows to reveal what is not available to almost no other method.

53:32.000 --> 53:38.000
Let's look at the typology of quality research, which is presented on the diagram.

53:38.000 --> 53:45.000
A quality interview can be individual, or it can be conducted with a group of people.

53:46.000 --> 53:51.000
Individual interviews can be conducted in person, that is, eye to eye,

53:51.000 --> 53:54.000
or they can be conducted by phone.

53:54.000 --> 53:57.000
This is also a very useful method.

53:57.000 --> 54:01.000
Group interviews are allocated to a separate category,

54:01.000 --> 54:10.000
which are conducted with a group of people, and are called a focus group.

54:11.000 --> 54:22.000
The problems of the quality of the collected data as a result of the interview generally require discussion.

54:22.000 --> 54:29.000
First of all, there is a question of the reliability of the data obtained.

54:29.000 --> 54:32.000
What is reliability?

54:32.000 --> 54:46.000
It is that these data can be relied on, and these data can be obtained again if the interview is repeated.

54:46.000 --> 54:51.000
Unfortunately, when we talk about collecting quality data,

54:51.000 --> 54:57.000
very often nothing can be repeated.

54:57.000 --> 55:06.000
Therefore, we must take care of ensuring the reliability of the data from the first time.

55:06.000 --> 55:12.000
Since the situation in business changes very quickly,

55:12.000 --> 55:26.000
it is necessary to recommend to the researcher to register absolutely all the collected data,

55:26.000 --> 55:33.000
so that if there is a doubt about the reliability of these data,

55:33.000 --> 55:42.000
it would be possible to upload a record archive and justify the conclusions made,

55:42.000 --> 55:49.000
or, so to speak, to see where and how additional research can be carried out

55:49.000 --> 55:55.000
to further justify the conclusions made.

55:56.000 --> 56:04.000
The assurance of the reliability of the data is directly related to the prejudice of collecting data.

56:04.000 --> 56:07.000
Moreover, this prejudice can be twofold.

56:07.000 --> 56:16.000
The prejudice of the participant of the interview and the prejudice of the interviewer.

56:16.000 --> 56:20.000
If we talk about the prejudice of the interviewer,

56:20.000 --> 56:28.000
the researcher must be internally ready to avoid this,

56:28.000 --> 56:34.000
and must treat exactly those whom he is asking.

56:34.000 --> 56:42.000
As for the prejudice of the participants, it can be related to a number of reasons.

56:42.000 --> 56:50.000
One of the reasons for the prejudice is that very often the person who is being asked

56:50.000 --> 56:56.000
assumes what they want to hear from him,

56:56.000 --> 57:07.000
and builds his answer in such a way as to satisfy the interviewer in the best way.

57:07.000 --> 57:15.000
He can also think that what I am going to say now will be told to my boss,

57:15.000 --> 57:25.000
and therefore he tries to change his answer a little, as if he said it without thinking about it.

57:28.000 --> 57:35.000
The prejudice of the interview participant can also be related to some personal issues.

57:35.000 --> 57:44.000
If the questions of the interviewer are related to some personal issues in his life,

57:44.000 --> 57:55.000
the person can go into a deaf defense and not answer the question correctly.

57:55.000 --> 58:02.000
Here good skills of the interviewer must be shown.

58:02.000 --> 58:08.000
He must be a good psychologist, he must read the non-verbal signs well,

58:08.000 --> 58:13.000
which the interview participant gives him,

58:13.000 --> 58:23.000
in order to stop in time, change the topic, rephrase the question, and get away from such problems.

58:23.000 --> 58:31.000
Another prejudice can be related to the group interviews.

58:31.000 --> 58:42.000
The interviewer does not want to give an answer in the presence of the third person.

58:42.000 --> 58:59.000
This problem can also be avoided if the researcher plans and forms the composition of people

58:59.000 --> 59:05.000
who will participate in the group interview.

59:05.000 --> 59:11.000
The next point is to provide validity and possibility of data generalization.

59:11.000 --> 59:18.000
It is difficult to overestimate the importance of qualitative data, it is very important.

59:18.000 --> 59:26.000
However, it is not easy to generalize qualitative data.

59:26.000 --> 59:33.000
If the interview was not conducted at the representative election,

59:33.000 --> 59:39.000
then the generalization may be completely unfair.

59:39.000 --> 59:46.000
And in general, to generalize qualitative data is a rather complicated problem.

59:47.000 --> 01:00:00.000
Therefore, it is necessary to conduct the interviews very carefully and select the participants for the future interview.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:08.000
A very important point of the interview is to set the questions.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:14.000
First of all, it is necessary to say that there are two types of questions.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:19.000
These are open questions and closed questions.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:28.000
Open questions are good because they allow the interview participant to describe the situation in his own words,

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:36.000
using his vocabulary, using his thoughts, feelings, and so on.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:43.000
Open questions usually start with the words how and why.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:47.000
How do you see the future of our company?

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:56.000
Why do you think we need to develop a branch network? And so on.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:10.000
Closed questions assume that the information should be clear or that a certain fact is confirmed.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:20.000
Usually, questions are asked in such a way that the person either gives an assessment of the event or simply says yes or no.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:26.000
Is it true that the new warehouse of ready-made products was opened in March? Yes or no.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:29.000
And there is nothing else here.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:37.000
Closed questions, by the way, can be used if a large number of interviews have been conducted,

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:48.000
subject to some statistical processing and get some quantitative characteristic of the studied phenomenon or event.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:59.000
Since the interview is conducted for a long time, and we are talking about the reliability of qualitative studies,

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:04.000
a separate emphasis should be placed on the registration of data.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:09.000
And there are three possible situations.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:18.000
The first one is that the researcher is recording during the interview.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:23.000
Is it good or bad? It depends on the situation.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:32.000
If the situation allows, it is better to record directly during the interview.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:42.000
To facilitate the task, you can prepare a tablet, divided into two, with a piece of paper.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:49.000
Each of you can have your own method, divided into two graphs.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:52.000
It is impossible to record and interview simultaneously.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:59.000
You can make short notes in the graph, what the person said and what you thought about it.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:02.000
And then you can sit down and think it over.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:09.000
When you have a canvas, it is quite easy to restructure it.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:18.000
If there is no such possibility, the researcher should understand by the reaction of the person he is asking.

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:23.000
If he sees that the person does not like that something is being recorded,

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:28.000
it is better to avoid this situation, to put it on your memory,

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:38.000
and to sit down and record the whole interview in detail right after the person has left.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:42.000
Of course, this is not the best option.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:47.000
There can be some overlays.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:51.000
The next way to register data is to make a wall.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:04:03.000
When a specially trained person records in detail what the researcher said,

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:07.000
what the researcher asked, and what the interview participant said.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:13.000
Recently, this method is used very rarely,

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:23.000
because our technical development has reached such heights that we can afford to use a dictaphone.

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:27.000
A dictaphone is a very good and convenient thing.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:33.000
It allows you to record all questions and answers.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:40.000
But using a dictaphone does not exclude recording.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:45.000
Because you cannot see any non-verbal signs on the dictaphone.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:55.000
And they can be extremely important when analyzing the received information.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:05.000
In your workbook, you have a table that illustrates in great detail the advantages and disadvantages of a dictaphone.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:09.000
I will not go into details, but I will definitely mention one thing.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:14.000
There is an ethical side to using a dictaphone.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:20.000
What a researcher should do, from the ethical point of view,

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:28.000
is to ask for the permission of the interview participant to use a dictaphone.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:35.000
If the interview participant does not agree with the use of a dictaphone,

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:43.000
the researcher should be ready to record the information in any other way.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:49.000
But using a dictaphone is not a panacea.

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:56.000
Because decoding a recording from a dictaphone is also a very difficult task.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:59.000
Telephone interviews.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:06.000
In what cases can telephone interviews be used?

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:22.000
As a rule, the advantage of a telephone interview is that it is very accessible to a remote participant.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:31.000
Let's say you want to interview or ask questions, working in a head office,

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:36.000
to managers of all regional subsidiaries of yours,

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:40.000
which are located in different parts of the world.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:45.000
It is expensive and long to go there.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:52.000
It is much easier to call and ask this question or a number of questions on the phone.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:55.000
It is cheap and fast.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:01.000
Relatively cheap, compared to the cost of a plane ticket.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:08.000
But telephone interviews have a number of limitations.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:20.000
The first of the limitations is that it is impossible to control the information received by the interviewee.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:23.000
This is very important.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:33.000
Because it can lead to a misunderstanding of the situation, to misplacing the emphasis, and so on.

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:39.000
Of course, you can guess by the voice about some things.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:46.000
For example, the degree of irritation of a person, the degree of his kindness.

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:58.000
Not for nothing, there is such a phrase in English literature as a smiling voice.

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:07.000
That is, on the phone, by the sound of a voice, it is clear whether a person is smiling or sitting with a grimace.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:11.000
But, nevertheless, this is a very strong limitation.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:19.000
In addition, telephone interviews are extremely not recommended to be conducted with people

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:23.000
with whom you have not had personal contact before.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:30.000
Because it can distort the information you receive.

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:43.000
Only after meeting a person in person, it is desirable to agree with this person

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:49.000
that if I have additional questions, I can call you on the phone.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:57.000
This will be ethical and correct in terms of receiving reliable information.

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:10.000
If necessary, you can call on the phone, but it is better to make this phone call with some permission, and so on.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:15.000
And we have to discuss the focus group.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:23.000
As already mentioned, the focus group is a group interview, that is, with several participants.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:33.000
In this case, the researcher performs the role of a moderator, that is, the organizer of a group discussion.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:43.000
Usually, such an interview is not structured, and the direction of the discussion is not controlled.

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:50.000
Only certain aspects of the topic to be discussed are highlighted.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:55.000
This is a high-quality method of gathering information.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:05.000
It allows to reveal different opinions, different understanding of the same problem to different people,

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:11.000
to understand how different phenomena are perceived by certain groups of people,

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:21.000
and its task is to determine the real attitude and view of people on a particular issue.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:30.000
But a group interview can be structured, partially structured,

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:36.000
when the moderator has a certain set of questions,

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:41.000
and those that must be discussed in this group.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:49.000
What is important and necessary to know about the focus group?

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:58.000
First of all, you need to pay attention to the selection of people to participate in the focus group.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:00.000
This is very important.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:08.000
It is important to have a personal psychological compatibility between people who will participate.

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:16.000
It is undesirable to invite the leaders and subordinates to one focus group,

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:29.000
because the latter can express their attitude to the discussed problem in a slightly different way in the presence of the leadership, and so on.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:37.000
It is very important to pay attention to the place of the focus group.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:41.000
Focus groups are usually not big.

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:46.000
The practice shows that 7-10 people are optimal.

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:48.000
Why so many?

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:54.000
Because if the number of people becomes larger,

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:00.000
then, first of all, the researcher, the moderator, cannot monitor the entire audience.

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:07.000
Some people just sit passively and do not participate in the discussion.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:15.000
If there are fewer participants, then the focus group is actually transformed into a personal interview.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:28.000
The main advantage of the focus group is to hear different points of view on the discussed problem,

01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:36.000
to understand different attitudes of people to the same discussed problem, and so on.

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:41.000
If we talk about the place of the focus group,

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:46.000
it is better to do it on the neutral territory.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:48.000
Neutral in quotation marks.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:58.000
It means not in the office of the leader, where the subordinates may feel constrained.

01:12:58.000 --> 01:13:08.000
In principle, the ideal option is to have a separate room.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:16.000
For example, in the company, it can be a room for negotiations,

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:20.000
which is neutral for all participants,

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:30.000
for the leader, if he is going to be invited, and for all other employees.

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:41.000
It is desirable that this room has the possibility to record audio and video.

01:13:42.000 --> 01:13:49.000
And we move on to the aspect of data registration in the focus group process.

01:13:50.000 --> 01:13:52.000
The possible forms of recording.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:54.000
There are three options.

01:13:55.000 --> 01:14:04.000
If there are no technical means of recording, then there are only two options.

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:11.000
Ideally, two people should conduct the focus group.

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:18.000
One performs the role of a moderator, the other leads the recording in parallel.

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:27.000
Since it is almost impossible to talk to an audience of 7-10 people and still have time to record something.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:33.000
If there is no second person, then, as in the case of an individual interview,

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:43.000
the moderator must make all the recordings immediately after the end of the group interview.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:53.000
And the ideal option is to record everything that is happening using audio or video technology.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:57.000
What can be noted here?

01:14:57.000 --> 01:15:02.000
First, it is necessary to ask from the point of view of ethics,

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:06.000
do people have permission to conduct audio or video technology.

01:15:06.000 --> 01:15:10.000
This has already become a standard procedure.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:14.000
You can't get away from this.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:20.000
And here, by the way, the issue of reliability of data collection is reflected.

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:28.000
If we force people to conduct the focus group,

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:40.000
and also remove them, we will get answers that will take us very far from the real situation.

01:15:40.000 --> 01:15:44.000
And then we will not get reliable data.

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:49.000
But here is the same problem that we discussed about the dictaphone.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:53.000
Deciphering these recordings is also a difficult task.

01:15:53.000 --> 01:15:57.000
It is time-consuming, and so on.

01:15:57.000 --> 01:16:05.000
I will emphasize once again that there are no perfect methods, but reliability must be ensured.

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:10.000
Therefore, when conducting qualitative studies,

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:17.000
a method is now adopted called triangulation.

01:16:17.000 --> 01:16:20.000
In translation from Latin, it is a triangle.

01:16:20.000 --> 01:16:29.000
That is, using the advantages of one method,

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:36.000
by combining methods, we can level the shortcomings of another

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:40.000
and ensure the reliability of our results.

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:51.000
Triangulation is a method of checking and improving the reliability and interpretation of data in a qualitative study.

01:16:51.000 --> 01:17:00.000
This method of checking comes to us from technical science, namely from geodesy.

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:13.000
There is a method of triangles that allows us to accurately determine the coordinates of a point on the terrain.

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:20.000
And we need to ensure absolute and accurate fixation of our data.

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:24.000
There are four types of triangulation.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:33.000
Three of them absolutely must be used in a qualitative study.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:44.000
We list them as data triangulation, researchers' triangulation, methodological triangulation, and theory triangulation.

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:48.000
If we talk about theory triangulation,

01:17:48.000 --> 01:17:59.000
then using the triangulation method itself is the best example of how this method works.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:05.000
As I said, it came from geodesy business research.

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:17.000
The same way, theory triangulation is the use of marketing theory, let's say, management of people,

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:22.000
and use it for research in the field of finance, for example.

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:32.000
That is, it is the use of theory from interrelated sciences in your research.

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:36.000
Data triangulation is very simple.

01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:40.000
This is what we have just talked about.

01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:53.000
Data must be obtained in several ways that complement each other and ensure the reliability of the result.

01:18:54.000 --> 01:19:11.000
Data triangulation means that we must use data for confirmation of a research hypothesis or answer to a research question,

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:17.000
both quantitative and qualitative research.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:25.000
Research triangulation is somewhat different and not always possible.

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:32.000
Research triangulation is possible when there is a group of researchers.

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:41.000
Regardless of each other, they receive certain data, as we said a little earlier in the example,

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:56.000
and then sit down together and compare the data obtained, making certain adjustments or conducting additional research.

01:19:57.000 --> 01:20:05.000
But if there is only one researcher, then it is impossible to triangulate researchers.

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:10.000
Therefore, methodological triangulation is very important for him,

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:19.000
that is, the use of different methods to obtain qualitative data.

01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:29.000
If a researcher has managed to conduct this triangulation principle in his research,

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:37.000
then it increases the validity of his research and, I think, practical significance.

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:44.000
The collected data must be processed and analyzed.

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:59.000
It is important to note that the question of analyzing qualitative data should be raised at the time of making a plan for future research.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:06.000
That is, while planning the methods you will use to collect data,

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:14.000
you need to think about how you will analyze them later during the research.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:23.000
If it is assumed that you will get information that is very diverse, difficult to classify,

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:34.000
then you need to think in advance about several other sources of information, methods of collecting this information, and so on.

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:44.000
We have already discussed that the analysis of qualitative data can and should be carried out at the stage of collecting information,

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:59.000
because it can contribute to the emergence of new ideas, to the change of the direction of research, and maybe even to the return to the original position.

01:22:00.000 --> 01:22:13.000
The next feature of the analysis of qualitative data is that standardized schemes cannot be used for their analysis.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:29.000
This is always a creative, flexible approach to analysis, although there are certain methods of analyzing qualitative data.

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:39.000
These methods can be divided into several stages or include the following operations.

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:52.000
First of all, this is the division of all data into separate categories and groups according to a certain characteristic, a separate characteristic.

01:22:52.000 --> 01:23:02.000
But in this case, the researcher's skill and ability to identify a characteristic characteristic should also be shown,

01:23:02.000 --> 01:23:08.000
according to which the data will be grouped into separate categories.

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:15.000
This method exists in different categories.

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:28.000
In principle, you can assign a certain code to each category and even do some kind of machine processing.

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:38.000
The data processed in this way can be combined into the so-called information unit,

01:23:38.000 --> 01:23:47.000
again, in the same way as in another discipline of logistics, which has the concept of a cargo unit,

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:56.000
that is, the combination of homogeneous items into one unit of accounting.

01:23:56.000 --> 01:24:11.000
I think you all bought some products with a small option and saw how 6 bottles of Coca-Cola were soldered into the film.

01:24:11.000 --> 01:24:14.000
This will be the cargo unit.

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:24.000
And for us, you and I, in research, in business, we will have to form such an information unit,

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:31.000
consisting of data that contains approximately homogeneous information.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:42.000
After we have divided our data into categories, the next step must be carried out,

01:24:42.000 --> 01:24:49.000
that is, to identify the interconnection between certain categories.

01:24:49.000 --> 01:24:58.000
Because in a separate form, they will not benefit us in any way.

01:24:58.000 --> 01:25:06.000
And only by identifying the interconnection between them, we can develop a system of categories

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:11.000
and implement what we talked about in the synthesis.

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:19.000
Next, we need to check the hypotheses in order to come to conclusions.

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:23.000
I will emphasize the word conclusions right away.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:37.000
The conclusions must be based strictly on the information, on the data that you received and described in your report.

01:25:38.000 --> 01:25:47.000
Very often, the conclusion is not based on the described, analyzed material,

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:56.000
one of the most standard mistakes, but on the fact that the researcher has, let's say, three, write, two in mind.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:03.000
He builds one of the conclusions on the research problem based on these two in mind.

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:05.000
This should not be done.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:11.000
How can we group the data we receive?

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:25.000
Most often, we do it by the moments listed below, by events, by people, let's say, by gender, by age, by products, materials.

01:26:25.000 --> 01:26:36.000
Let's say, we will talk about the Chepchiks, about the space vehicles, and so on.

01:26:36.000 --> 01:26:39.000
About resources, costs, and income.

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:44.000
So, grouping is not an exhaustive list.

01:26:44.000 --> 01:26:51.000
It can be supplemented depending on what has been studied.

01:26:51.000 --> 01:27:03.000
And just like in the end of the first topic, in the end of the second topic, you will find questions and tasks for self-checking.

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:13.000
Once again, scroll through your workbook and try to work through this task.

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:24.000
And after that, we will move on to the last topic, the third topic, ethics in management research.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:33.000
Ethics in management research

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:43.000
How important are ethics in management research?

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:58.000
When we talk about ethics, we think about medicine, but ethics in management research is becoming more and more important.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:10.000
And although there is no such rule as what it means to conduct ethical management research or business research,

01:28:10.000 --> 01:28:15.000
nevertheless, there is a reason to discuss these issues.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:17.000
What is ethics?

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:25.000
These are questions about the development of moral norms, which can help to assess the situation.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:41.000
These are the moral values that a person has or does not have, which can be violated, and so on.

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:50.000
As a rule, ethics norms precede the norms of the law.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:29:00.000
Each of us, one way or another, assesses whether we have acted ethically in relation to the law or not.

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:10.000
When a researcher plans his research, he must ask himself the same question.

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:16.000
How ethical will it be to ask a researcher a question?

01:29:16.000 --> 01:29:23.000
How ethical will it be to involve him in this research? And so on.

01:29:25.000 --> 01:29:36.000
Ethics norms are aimed at warning of the problems that may arise.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:41.000
But the laws are written as a rule.

01:29:41.000 --> 01:29:46.000
When there is a precedent, it was violated and the law was passed.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:50.000
That is, after a certain event has occurred.

01:29:50.000 --> 01:29:53.000
The parable of the Voivodess has probably already become a case.

01:29:53.000 --> 01:30:01.000
It may not be related to ethics, but it illustrates very well how something is written after the fact.

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:11.000
After an American grandmother washed her dog in a washing machine, and another one dried her dog in a microwave,

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:23.000
we can now read the instructions on how to use the equipment that are not familiar to us.

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:32.000
Recently, when I bought a frying pan, I read that it is not recommended to put a handle on the front of the stove,

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:37.000
so that the child running past does not push it on himself.

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:41.000
It would seem that's all.

01:30:41.000 --> 01:30:45.000
But back to the questions of ethics.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:49.000
What are the ethical limits?

01:30:50.000 --> 01:30:58.000
At the moment, two ethical aspects are being considered.

01:30:58.000 --> 01:31:07.000
This is deontology, or otherwise the principle of rights and the principle of justice, and teleology.

01:31:07.000 --> 01:31:09.000
What is deontology?

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:15.000
It is based on two criteria of the assessment of activity.

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:18.000
The first is universality and the second is appeal.

01:31:18.000 --> 01:31:21.000
What does universality mean?

01:31:21.000 --> 01:31:34.000
It means that everyone should be treated equally, without infringing on someone's rights or giving someone their incentives.

01:31:34.000 --> 01:31:47.000
The principle of appeal says that people should be treated the way you would like them to be treated.

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:56.000
Then it is believed that moral norms will be observed from the point of view of deontology.

01:31:56.000 --> 01:32:01.000
This is from the point of view of the principle of rights.

01:32:01.000 --> 01:32:11.000
But from the point of view of the principle of justice, three categories are distinguished.

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:15.000
Distributive, punishing and compensating.

01:32:15.000 --> 01:32:18.000
What is distributive?

01:32:18.000 --> 01:32:24.000
It means that everyone should be treated equally.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:34.000
Distributive means that everyone should be treated equally.

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:51.000
Punishing means that if a person acted unethically, violated someone's rights, he should be punished accordingly.

01:32:52.000 --> 01:33:04.000
The compensating category says that if the principle of justice in relation to the participant in this case of the study was violated,

01:33:04.000 --> 01:33:10.000
then a person has the right to be compensated.

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:27.000
If the participant in the study's rights were violated, for example, his right to be heard, his right to receive additional information,

01:33:27.000 --> 01:33:35.000
then the researcher must somehow compensate for the damage done.

01:33:35.000 --> 01:33:46.000
Deontology is the principle of the benefit of the person.

01:33:46.000 --> 01:33:49.000
It is the theory of benefit for the person.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:34:09.000
It is important to understand that morally, ethically, deontology is something that does not cause damage to a person.

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:17.000
Let's take an example.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:27.000
A country is fighting for democracy in another small country.

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:35.000
From the point of view of the principle of common good, it seems that they are doing well.

01:34:35.000 --> 01:34:49.000
But if we think about those hundreds and thousands of people with a damaged fate or who no longer exist in this world,

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:55.000
then from the point of view of deontology, these actions are immoral.

01:34:55.000 --> 01:35:01.000
If we return to the business of research, what principle should we profess?

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:05.000
Deontology or teleology?

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:10.000
We have not yet talked about teleology, but let's answer the question for ourselves.

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:17.000
Should we apply the principle of deontology in governance studies or not?

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:28.000
We should take care of the moral behavior of the researcher towards each participant,

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:38.000
regardless of the benefits that may be obtained as a result of infringement of the rights of these participants.

01:35:39.000 --> 01:35:48.000
Unfortunately, the answer to this question can be twofold.

01:35:48.000 --> 01:36:01.000
From the point of view of high theory and high ethics, governance studies should be conducted in such a way

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:07.000
that no participant is harmed.

01:36:08.000 --> 01:36:17.000
But unfortunately, this principle is often ignored in real business situations.

